segments.text: The history of the island, there's probably good documentation of the history.
But there's not much documentation of the government role in the history.
The government just was not there.
I mean, it was extremely corrupt.
It was extremely non-professional until the late, late 50s or 60s.
So you didn't have a situation like many other communities would have when it was more of a planning presence.
Of course, the natural disaster they had there in the hurricane at the turn of the century was responsible for the seawall and some other things they did.
It was also responsible for the demise of Galveston because the principal of Galveston never really recovered from that.
They were the major city in Texas at that time.
And after that hurricane, the damage and the deaths that resulted from that, investments didn't really come back to Galveston.
Well, let's see if we can find some more things.
How have the following influences affected planning in the community?
Ethnic.
Has there been much of an ethnic impact?
Galveston's, well, ethnicity, if you look at race, for example, probably close to 40% of Galveston is black.
And it's, in a sense, almost a ghetto, because those people live in one small area in Galveston.
And they're not spread out.
To me, it was important to do the planning for those areas.
We did have some areas that were low income that didn't necessarily have historical structures.
The poverty level was such that those structures had long since been destroyed.
And the historical value and ability to restore them didn't really exist.
During the latter part of the time I was there, there was a kind of awakening in the black community to some extent.
There was not much support for neighborhood planning at that time.
I went into one of the more advanced higher income levels to do the first neighborhood plan, East End neighborhood.
The second neighborhood was gonna be the black community.
We did have a group come in and receive a grant.
from the city under the Community Development Block Grant to do a neighborhood plan for one of the black neighborhoods.
But that was done more as a political payoff.
The manager told me, we need to support this group.
And they need the money.
And this is our way of showing it.
Because they weren't competent.
They weren't qualified to do it.
And I was very disturbed and disappointed to see that money being wasted in it.
In my way of thinking, the worst thing you can do is do a bad planning project.
You're better off doing no planning project.
That project eventually failed.
The consultants did not produce a report.
And the city staff had to come back in here and save that program.
But a couple of people at that time brought in, gosh, I can't remember his name, from Cincinnati.
Gosh, I can't remember his name.
Very well known black man who had been able to revitalize part of Cincinnati.
I wish I remember his name.
I'm disappointed for not knowing that.
He wanted to create a neighborhood housing service program.
He wanted to kind of a bootstrap operation.
And there were some people in the black community that were very sympathetic to what he had to say.
And I think there was a renewal or an awakening of the political aspects of this.
And a couple of, in fact, I think as I was leaving a black community,
P.J.
Thomas, maybe, I don't remember his name for sure, but a black man was appointed to our council, or our commission, rather.
And now I understand there is a, last time I was down there in Galveston, one of the councilmen was black, and it used to be all Anglo, all male.

And the first year I was down there, they had one woman in the council, and they now have a woman running for mayor at this time, who was a strong advocate of planning, that I knew when I was down there, she was one of the behind-the-scenes folks that I worked with and tried to
give her ammunition to use in her interest.
And she ran several years ago for council and was elected.
She'll be a good mayor.
But I think there was kind of an awakening there.
The black community was almost invisible.
It's hard to believe that with a population of that level that they would be invisible.
But they were.
They were visible politically.
They were invisible in the culture and in the very life of the city.
You didn't see black people in Galveston Island.
You didn't see them on the beaches.
You didn't see them in the stores and shops.
I knew how many blacks there were supposed to be there from the census.
But it didn't take me very long before I wondered where on earth they were at.
You just did not see the minority community on that island when I was there.
Well, why don't we take a divergence from Galveston and talk a little bit about Corpus Christi.
Talk about Corpus.
Corpus, you know, I hope in the oral histories here that somebody, and I assume they have it, talked to Bill Anderson.
I got there just after Bill Anderson retired.
One of the biggest disappointments in my life.
One reason I had been going to Galveston was that he was down there.
He was there for 25 years.
It's a well-planned city because of that continued presence on his part there.
I was hired as a senior planner.
I had the responsibility for
revising and updating their zoning ordinance.
That was my initial responsibility.
Simon Eisner, a national consultant, had been hired to draft, or really to analyze, the deficiencies in the city's zoning ordinance.
It was a Harlem Bartholomew ordinance they had.
And he reviewed it, produced an 80-, 90-page, 100-page report on changes that needed to be made.
The city's strategy was to, rather than just make all those changes at one time, it was to work its way through those changes.

Simon Eisner probably would have done that under his consulting agreement, but he had a running with the city manager, Marvin Townsend, at the council meeting where he, in essence, lectured the city manager for being rude and insensitive to the planning director at a public hearing.
This is a unique situation.
Marvin Townsend was a very strong, loyal city manager, ruled the city of Galveston with an iron fist, an iron hand,
Bill Anderson, the planning director, was one of the few people who he did not control, who had some ability to have freedom to express themselves to the council.
A sense of threat to the manager, if you wanted to look at it in a negative sense to him.
But at one of the council meetings where Simon Eisner was in attendance presenting this ordinance, a planning matter came up and the planning director had spoken on something.
Marvin Townsend got up and told the council that the planning director didn't know what he was talking about, that he was wrong in this matter, and he was really not paying attention to him.
It was a real put-down.

Well, at some time before that meeting was over, when Simon Eisner got up to talk about his consultant report, he proceeded to lecture the council and the manager about the impropriety of a manager saying
the things he had said to the planning director, questioning the planning director's judgment in doing so in the situation that was done.
Townsend didn't use a lot of tact in that kind of situation when he was dealing with this department here.
And he publicly humiliated the planning director and chastised him.
And Eisner just lectured down the city manager for having done that.
Nobody talks like that to the city manager, to Marvin Townsend.
So at the end of that meeting, Mr. Townsend, former planning director, that Mr. Eisner was no longer welcome at Corpus Christi.
He didn't want to see his face again.
And so that's why Simon Eisner never finished that.
Well, anyway, I was hired.
For about a year, I worked through some of these changes in the ordinance.
We were able to make a good many of them.
We had a 701 planning program.
It was not doing well.
The staff in charge of it really did not know what they were doing.
And they were floundering.
And the head of the program resigned and left.
And at that point, then they asked me if I would be willing to do that job, run the 701 program as well as the zoning ordinance.
And I was made to, at that time I was a senior planner.
And I was senior planner in charge of research and development.
And the research and development was supposed to be the zoning ordinance.
But they expanded that to include the development of the comprehensive plan.
So the next two years, two and a half years,
I ran that program with three or four other staff people, and we produced a comprehensive plan.
We produced a land use element, a park and open space element, a library facilities element, utilities element, school master plan elements, police facilities element, fire facilities element.
Basically, we produced a series of independent reports that constituted a comprehensive plan.
We did the economic determinants study.
We did a physical determinants study.
We did a social determinants study.
These were all separate reports ranging from one to 200 pages in size.
And then we produced all the elements of the plan.
None of those planning elements were ever presented to the city council or the planning commission.
They were very well known technically.
The housing element was probably one of the most best illustrations, best examples of a comprehensive plan that I've ever been involved with.
Bob Cornish had reviewed that with us and helped us as kind of a free advisor on certain parts of the plan.
And we were developing what TJ Kent would call a unified summary, which was very innovative and was
at the cutting edge of planning technology at that point.
We satisfied the 701 requirements.
HUD accepted those reports.
We received probably $140,000 one year, $80,000 one year, maybe $250,000 in federal assistance to do those plans.
It was quite substantial.
Paid for these five staff people that worked on this plan and published and printed it.
At the same time, I was involved superficially and peripherally with the Goals for Corpus Christi program.
That was a two-year program that was run in the direction of John Lewis, who is now the executive director of Goals for Dallas.
John had been a member of our planning staff.
Outstanding goals program.
Again, one of the most technically sound goals programs that I have ever read about in any literature anywhere.
We had 10,000 to 12,000 residents participate in the goals program.
outstanding, I mean, an astounding, outstanding percentage, especially in light of the fact that we're in a bilingual community with 40, 45% of the community Mexican-American.
So we had to do everything with that view in mind.
We're also in a low-income area.
Galveston-Corpus Christi was 148th, I believe, in the SMSAs in per capita income.
Both of those are usually impediments to citizen participation in the GOES program, outstanding GOES program.
The city manager did not support that GOES program.
The mayor did not support that GOES program.
The response when the results of the program were presented to the council was great work, good try, too bad more people didn't participate so it would have been worthwhile.
But it was worth a shot at it.
It was too bad it failed.
and they just swept it away in the closet.
In essence, the city manager did the same thing in the comprehensive plan.
He did not agree with the process that we used.
He did not like policies.
He was opposed to the use of principles, concepts, and standards.
He was opposed to any analysis which suggested that there were deficiencies in the city of any type whatsoever.
Probably going back, he was most opposed to the idea of the concept behind policies.
He was not interested in the city council establishing policies.
My negative biased assessment of it was that he saw this as a threat to his authority, his dominance over the council, his freedom to make decisions.
He buried it.
He boxed them up.
They were put in a closet somewhere.
And the last I heard was they might have even been burned.
He was afraid they might
following the public domain.
Somebody might come in and find them or see them or whatever it is.

But I will say in the two and a half years there, the plan that was produced was as technically as sound, maybe as good of an example of what a comprehensive plan ought to be and could be of anything I had seen.
It was kind of the culmination of my career.
I had done elements and components of plans in various cities and at various times, but never had I had the two and a half years
to do all of the components for one community.

And I was able to do that and able to apply some of the newer ideas about how to communicate, how to do a plan that was understandable, manageable, dealt with enough issues, but not too many issues, manageable in that sense, and put these plans together in a format where people could see these interrelationships and linkages between these elements.
which is a challenge to us.
It's a challenge I'm not sure the profession has been able to respond to.
Technically, it was just outstanding.
You know, it just destroyed me to have to walk away from it and to see it not be accepted.
But I recognized I had to do that.
The man who was city manager, the man who is manager, is boss.
And he was the boss, and he was opposed to these things.
I think the most disappointing thing was that toward the last year I worked in that program, I had asked not to do it.
because of some of the rejections I received from him on earlier elements, I had tried to get off of that and say, hey, let someone else do this.
Or let's not do these elements, because the manager doesn't want them.
And this is a mistake.
And the planning director, who at that time was Larry Winger was, in essence, the assistant director.
Gosh, I can't remember his name.
It's a Mexican-American fellow who was the planning director.
And he met with the manager, and the manager was adamant that he wanted a plan.
He would use the plan.
And I had given him an outline of what the plan was, and he was committing to that outline.
And I told the planning director, I said, from my discussions I've had with the manager earlier here, this does not represent what he wants to do.
This is a mistake to do a plan like this.
And the planning director said, no, he was...
He was committed to it.
He wanted to do it.
He wanted that plan.
And so we did it.
And that was a profit fulfilled, unfortunately.
The manager came back and reacted exactly like I knew he would do.
Okay.
Okay.
Well, thank you very much.
All right.
